Ammo is "GP21" ball ammo which is a SS109 / M855 type load, made to stricter quality standards than NATO requires. Ammo is brass case, non-corrosive and reloadable boxer primed. The projectile contains a steel penetrator and is magnetic, but it is not color coded with a green tip like US ammo. GGG cal. 5.56×45 mm NATO Ball rounds are being manufactured according to the requirements of STANAG 4172. In 2005 cartridges were successfully qualified at NATO European Regional Test Center (ERTC) in UK and GGG gained right to mark its cartridges with NATO interchangeability sign. GP21 is a marking of standard GGG 5.56×45 mm cartridges produced in accordance to the requirements for SS109. Products have confirmed NSN (NATO Stock Number). NATO Design number is AC/225-130A.

title: For Sale:  LC Smith side by side 12 ga. shotgun - 1901 Grade 2 , ejectors
postcontent: Rare 1901 LC Smith grade 2, with special ordered ejectors and optional 32" barrels.  The serial number and round, roller type forend release (only available for one year) date this gun to 1901 - it has Crown fluid steel barrels that have bright bores and ring like a bell when tested.  The gun appears original, the surfaces, while the finish is well worn, have no rust pitting.  The stocks are in good shape for a gun of this age, with the customary handling marks, dings, and dents, the major distractions being a small, cosmetic crack starting at the back of one of the side plates, and some old chipping on the forend on one side near where it meets the forearm metal.  The top stock screw (under the opening lever), also does not appear to be original.  The forarm has the ebony tip insert.  The receiver is engraved in the grade 2 fashion, with a quail on one side and a woodcock on the other...I believe that some, if not most of the guns in this grade had a duck engraving instead of the woodcock.  The action locks up tight, although the lever is slightly left of center.  The chambers measure out as 2-3/4" and the chokes are tight, as they are in most of the pre 1913 Smiths...they measure out as full and extra full.  Everything seems to function properly.  There is some roughness of the metal at the bottom of the gun where the forend meets the receiver, it appears to be easy to smooth out if you'd so desire.  The gun, especially the receiver, would cosmetically benefit by a light rubdown with copper wool and oil to remove some of the surface discoloration.  While it's always good policy to have these old doubles looked at by a qualified gunsmith prior to use, I personally can see nothing about it that would disqualify it for use with shells of the loads and pressures for which it was designed.  A nice, harder to find ejector gun from one of America's top side by side shotgun makers.  If you'd like more photos or information, please write.I will ship for $40 to valid FFL holders...buyers can make arrangements with a local FFL holder for transfer.  You must be over the age of 18 to purchase this gun, with a valid drivers license or photo ID.  You must be legally able to purchase and own firearms, and not be a felon or wanted by law enforcement.

Read details below
 
 
The new AR-556 has a gas-impingement system, just like the original AR 15 rifle design. The AR is a gas-operated rifle that uses the expanding gasses from the firing sequence to unlock the bolt directly via a tube that passes from under the front site, to a gas key connection on top of the bolt carrier. Most other gas operated rifles – including Ruger’s SR series – use a gas piston and op-rod to unlock the bolt after firing. The AK, M1, M14, the new M4-A4, and a host of others use a version of that basic mechanism.
 
The chamber is cut (out of the factory) for the 5.56 (and .223) round and utilizes the improved M4 feed ramp for increased reliability.
 
The gas piston mechanism results in a much cleaner firing system; all the carbon fouling stays on the end of the piston-more or less. The gas impingement system is like a smog device for your car: all the gunk ends up in the engine, or in this case, the bolt and carrier.  It’s a much dirtier arrangement. However, the gas-impingement rifle has much less reciprocating mass, giving it an edge in accuracy
 
Designed to reliably fire bullet weights up to (at least) 77 grains (and down to 35 grains) in weight.
 
The lower Receiver is standard with it six-position stock and military trigger. The trigger broke at eight pounds and is an improvement from most out-of-the-box military M4s.  The hand grip is not standard M4; it is shaped for a better feel.  The entire rifle is finished in a black oxide. No front sling swivel, but there is an attachment point for one as well as a bayonet, bipod, or other device.
